instructional assistant does anyone work as an instructional assistant in a public school system if so what is the nature of the work any info is appreciated detarover i actually did find that site earlier but i was wanting to have someone answer who has worked this occupation with some advice and info thanks much ooops datarover sorry hello fellow thirty something and lover of 's rock i've been a teacher for years now but before that i worked as an paraprofessional teacher's aide for five years basically you work under the direction of the classroom teacher you'll probably be monitoring and helping students with special needs and learning disabilities you may also be asked to make copies laminate stuff some basic clerical stuff pay isn't the best but it's not horrific either nowadays you can expect to start at around or per hour to start you will only be paid for the days of school no vacation or holiday pay you will most likely receive pretty decent benefits though which is a plus you'll be expected to work the full day but won't have to attend teacher's professional days or anything like that you'll also have an annual review and given yearly raises although they're usually small like cents per hour you'll also get some sick time and personal days too i enjoyed my time as an aide no lesson planning or correcting one word of advice though don't try to up the teacher or talk in the lunchroom about a teacher doing something poorly it will come back to haunt you good luck and rock on i'm a father of two girls we're leading parrallel lives Education in the People's Republic of China Education in Japan Education in the United States Education in Hong Kong No Child Left Behind Act Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban Shaggy dog story Teacher Education in Romania Graduate school Homeschooling Social Security (United States) Japanese tea ceremony Kodocha Blackjack Great Teacher Onizuka Nurse A Course In Miracles 